</div><p></p><p> And they will provide him with his safe space tonight. They will welcome him, and they will fete him, and they will tell him not to care. That the press and the pollsters and his shadow cabinet colleagues and his backbenchers and the pundits – they’re all wrong! <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12031842/Winning-the-Oldham-by-election-isnt-a-triumph-for-Jeremy-Corbyn.-Its-the-minimum.html" target="_blank">Look at Oldham! Look at his triumph in Oldham!</a> And look at his triumph in the Labour leadership election! And look at all those new members joining the Labour Party! </p><p> “It’s working. Corbynism is working. You’re working,” they will tell him. “You keep going Jeremy. We’re right behind you. You tell the rest of them 'screw you'.” </p><p> And so he will. He will stand amongst his friends and do just that. He will say to the party he leads “screw you”. He will say to the MPs he leads: “screw you”. He will say to the British people: “screw you”. </p><p> As I say, there is part of me that wants to respect Jeremy Corbyn for this. For his utter disregard, his open contempt, for anyone who does not share his strange, twisted view of the nation and world he inhabits. </p><p> But screw him. I don’t. </p><p> <iframe class="tg-card" data-id="f51c66df-9261-449b-8732-1127112debd3" frameborder="0" height="259" id="player3" scrolling="no" src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/breakoutCards/f51c66df-9261-449b-8732-1127112debd3.html" style="float: left; margin: 0px 0px 10px; height: 528px;" width="540"></iframe><script src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/assets/_scripts/embed-card.js"></script>  </p></div>

